European inflation slides into food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the dizzying rise in food prices.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, recording - after 2.6 percent of the month in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - the Union Statistics Office in Luxembourg announced.
Official forecasts were only likely to give 3 percent — Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, along with rising commodity prices and the reduction of forced labour, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: “negotiations” about inflation must be negotiated so that it does not have to intervene later on.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, beat the 12-year record; while in Spain it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation shot up in the euro area as a result of the galloping food and energy prices.
Quotas at the end of wheat increased by 88 per cent, and so the soy quota reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market rose 52 percent this year, reaching nearly $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, but by 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to double interest rates during 2008.
