In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
Several thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals this year, primarily due to the misuse of antibiotics.
The prevailing hygiene conditions in hospitals, bed-wetting and staff overload do not favor infection control, says the head of the department of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of Hospital J<0xC3><0xA1>nos.
In a hospitalized man after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
One injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient soon afterwards had to return to the hospital as a result of MRSA infection and since then no major surgery has been possible due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10, 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multidrug-resistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, head of the department of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections produced by multidrug-resistant agents has certainly been recorded, the rest is not known.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One-third of humans carry the bacterium Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their nose without causing any disease.
Infections produced by SA (e.g., throat inflammation, amygdalitis, skin infections, wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once overly or improperly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics are transformed into bacteria that are highly resistant to antibiotics and quickly become infected under inappropriate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as infections of wounds or septicemia in the first place to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, patients with the weakened organism, elderly or people of low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of Hospital J<0xC3><0xA1>nos there is nothing special in MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to Antibiotics
“These patients are isolated, nursing staff take care of them in rubber gloves and mask and there are antibiotics suitable for their treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are pre-tested to check for MRSA in their body, but even so, infection cannot be avoided in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA hospital infections in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of formation and infection with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA in their body.
However, in Hungarian hospitals it is not fashionable to take microbiological samples.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient, said the head of the department of the epidemiology center.
The European Union makes strict recommendations for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
Antibiotic therapy should be directed, i.e., microbiological tests should be performed to prevent resistance to drugs, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of outpatients or in basic care - said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
It is saved with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through health care staff.
Therefore, hand washing plays a very important role, the use of rubber gloves and masks, however also in this sense considerable shortcomings are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is infected by droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least a distance of 1.5 meters.
Regrettably, it can also be experienced - Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz added - that in less favorable economic-situated hospitals is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater likelihood of infection.
In the opinion of Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, where appropriate prevention measures are met, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the pathogen infection can be stopped.
Government Program against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Sickness Insurance Fund, so in all countries it fights against it.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The program appears to be successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multidrug-resistant agents (including MRSA) and that of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
