The Minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 level, regardless of whether or not the “agreement after 2012” will be signed and is willing to commit to reducing even 30 percent if the other major developed regions of the world and their developing countries are also in line with their commitments.
G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol pledged to decrease by 5.2 per cent, within this the then 15 EU member states committed to meet an 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce by 6% the greenhouse gas emissions from the 1985-87 period, which our country will meet," the Ministry of the Environment said in a statement.
It is very much at stake in Bali, since in two years it will have to sign the international agreement on long-term climate policy, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed by after 2012. In this case the reduction commitments, assumed in the Kyoto Protocol, would not be immediately followed by a new international system of reduction of emigrants,
With this, the reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase of more than 2<0xC2><0xB0>C of the Earth’s average temperature could not be prevented, according to scientists, which would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British Army recruits on YouTube
Units of the British army in a video distributor publish footage of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First, the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube’s services: Special Forces deployed in Afghanistan since March 2006 are loading videos about their actions against the Taliban.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in the general body of Kandahar operations, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
There are already 139 recordings from the air force soldiers that have been uploaded in this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of actions carried out in both Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the air force had uploaded the videos with recruitment objectives, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defense they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the British army's presence abroad.
This type of propaganda almost costs nothing compared to conventional television spots of recruitment – said defense expert Gordon Mackenzie – instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans have made a video game.
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the meticulously edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear on the distributor, for example about the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers speak as a maximum of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fighters.
In addition, from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, numerous videos have already been uploaded to the Internet recorded in real operations, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different way to recruit with the free downloadable shooting video games called America’s Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly instead of the soldiers.
