The party is not always written with red numbers
In Hungary, the law accurately defines the days that are written with red numbers on the calendar and has already become a widespread practice that around the holidays - that the next year will be less - reorganize the working days.
Not even in the EU or in North America are parties unitary.
Hungarian laws make a difference between a national holiday, a state holiday and a public holiday.
Festive days are mainly related to religious festivals and historical ephemerals.
Let’s celebrate the New Year as well: both the last day of the old year, and the first day of the new year is festive – the latter especially so that you can rest those who have spent celebrating the old year.
Throughout the year we have eleven red-numbered parties on the calendar.
It is a national holiday on 15 March in memory of the revolution of 1848 and on 23 October, a commemorative day of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrate the founding of the State, on May 1st, the Labor Day, on November 1st and 2nd, we remind our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, in our country are two-day holidays Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, so it often becomes a bridge when before or after the holiday there is a single working day.
In exchange for the extended weekends like this, during the previous Saturdays you cannot be absent from work or school.
It is the Minister of Labour who regulates in his specific decree when it is necessary to work exactly in exchange for the day directly before or after the party.
This legal standard is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and public officials.
It is not mandatory, however, for companies and service institutions that, due to their function, work continuously even during holidays.
This year the order of work can only be changed around the holidays of the end of the year: from December 24 practically life is stopped in the country, as according to experience, most people "bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
Next year several of our holidays will coincide with mid- or weekends, so there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
First, the agenda around the work party will be modified so that, for four consecutive days, the workers can rest.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day, so that in return on Friday May 2nd will be a festive day.
The other change relates to the 23rd of October party: on Saturday 18th of October, you will have to work instead of Friday 24th.
On the other hand, the next year during the end of the year party can be rest, since from December 24 it will not be worked almost anywhere, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
