Congress approves transposition of Mifid, which entered into force on November 1
In parallel to its parliamentary process, which ended today with the vote by the Congress of the amendments incorporated into the draft in the Senate, the Government has submitted to public hearing the regulations to be developed by the new law, with the aim of both entering into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the effort made by deputies and senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulations in order to ensure the protection of investors and regulate in detail the activity of the entities for the markets to function efficiently.
The Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, involves the modernisation of financial markets, while reinforcing investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and fostering cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new regulation will allow to provide financial advisory services to both specialized firms and individuals or legal entities and create a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advisory societies (FIs), which join the securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the execution of operations on financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are added to multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current exchange managers.
The Act also obliges investment services companies to disclose information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and forms of risk management and requires them to keep a record of all operations they perform, to facilitate oversight by the CNMV.
In its passage by the Congressional Economics Commission, several modifications were incorporated, among which it highlights that securitized debts are considered a “complex” financial instrument given its high risk to the investor, which has been demonstrated with the debt of high-risk U.S. mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally delimit the functions that graduates in Economics and Business can develop 30 years after the actual decree that delimits the professional functions reserved for economists was passed in 1977.
For its part, the Senate incorporated the creation of new figures in the financial sector, such as that of the mediator, who will work on behalf of others, will not require authorization from the CNMV and will be able to provide its services of marketing products and customer acquisition to different investment companies at once.
