Buses bring refugees back to work – and the fight against Al Qaeda
The first buses with Iraqi refugees from Syria began arriving in Baghdad yesterday, expelling the refugees who were left without cash, without visa extensions and those who expected the city to return to normal.
Some had even returned to fight the militants who led them out of their homes.
At the Mansour bus station, even before the arrival of 800 people from Damascus in an official government convoy consisting of a dozen buses, the terminal was filled with refugees from Syria and Jordan who had returned in private transport.
“I decided to go to Syria after they killed many doctors in Baghdad,” said Sabah al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
“I came back today for what I saw on TV and what I read in the newspapers, about what happened in Baghdad and it’s safe now.”
“They say Mahdi’s army stopped killing people,” he says, referring to Shiite militia of religious militant cleric Moqtada al-Sadr, who ordered his troops to stop for a moment.
Qassim al Atwani, a 38-year-old Shia teacher in the Sunni area of Amariyah, returned with his two children because it was impossible to renew his visa to Syria because the regime does not want Iraqis working in their country.
His Shi’ite neighbors in Amariyah called him on the phone to tell him that an allied U.S. force helped take Al-Qaeda out of its stronghold west of the capital, and urged him to return.
One of Jordan’s recent arrivals was the head of a Sunni and Shia tribe who had been driven from their home in Sleikh north of Baghdad by a grenade attack, after urging citizens to rise up against Al-Qaeda.
He had come to fight.
“Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they had started an anti-Al-Qaeda militia in Sleikh and that they needed my support and that of my colleagues.”
“That’s why I came back today,” said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many said they were drawn to the growing calm in the capital since U.S. troops established groups of “worried citizens,” armed and working in cooperation with the U.S. military to defend their neighborhoods.
But many claimed to have returned for visa denial and lack of money in Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis settled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, a 51-year-old father of three, gave voice to the common suspicion among the exiles that Nouri al-Maliki, the Shiite prime minister, asked the Syrian government to impose restrictions on refugees’ visas to force people to return.
More than two and a half million people believe they have fled the country because of the sectarian death squads.
"We were fine until al-Maliki visited Syria and urged the government to stop granting visas to Iraqis, to force them to return to Iraq," he said.
“I can’t believe in a government that supports the criminals who set my house on fire after I left it.”
Part of the reason for the cessation of violence is that Sunnis have been expelled from Shia areas and vice versa, relaxing the tension.
There is a fear that a sudden wave of refugees will bring sectarian tensions back up and the struggle begins.
