Venus: twin brother of Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most similar to Earth, something that had not yet been proposed. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and swirls in the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
For the past three decades, researchers have suspected that there could be rays on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus, the rays fall from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California at Los Angeles to the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous Urey-Miller origin model, lightning caused life on Earth: storms may have caused reactions in the ocean that, for their part, had given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it is not so: if there ever was life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there can be no life on the surface of Venus: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface they reign temperatures of 500<0xC2><0xB0>C, oscillating so that temperatures can be reached below zero.
“Possibly, Venus is a ‘devilish’ twin of Earth, but it remains a twin,” Russell said.
The main objective of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many "Nature" articles, according to the researchers, highlight not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
“This also demonstrates that neighboring planets have more common features with Earth than we had assumed,” ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, the researchers also discovered in the southern polar region a vortex formed by the fastest rotating clouds.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high Earth's atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has a mass almost equal to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet is also called a morning star or evening star orbiting the Sun for nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not look much like Earth, scientists start from the base that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
Water had accumulated on both planets that remained on Earth in the oceans, but on Venus dissociated in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
