They are not wooden boxes.
He who relates the terms Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but does not think of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that weighs on Warhol's list of works.
Most of the ninety-four "type" gloss-boxes on this list are fake.
After a few months ago the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" also raised doubts about the authenticity of Brillo-Boxes from 1968 by Andy Warhol, the Museum Moderna Museet in Stockholm conducted internal investigations and came to disappointing conclusions: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which are the former director of the museum, are the "Brillo-Boxes", and the former director of the museum "Mull<0xC3><0xB3>t", are the "Mull<0xC3><0xB3>o" in the mull<0xC3><0xB3>.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Glass-Boxes" in New York, painted the wooden boxes red, blue and white, with the same sample that they had "Glass" soap powder cartons.
According to Warhol, in the exhibition of his 1968 works at the Museum Moderna Museet there were exposed hundreds of cardboard boxes. These were not made by Warhol (due to expenses), but were brought directly from the "Grill" cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but examples (which were only objects) exhibited.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed to produce in Sweden some wooden glints, but they were not exhibited at the Modern Museum.
Witnesses at the time now speak of almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auctions as originals of the "Stockholm-type" "Glass-Boxes" authorized by Andy Warhol.
At auctions some of them were purchased for more than $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous museum director Pontus Hultén made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden they were produced and exposed almost a hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left to him.
But actually, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malm<0xC3><0xB6> for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time Warhol had already died three years ago.
Lars Bystr<0xC3><0xB6>m, the head of the Moderna Museet Museum’s curators, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three of the Swedish private property that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm. They were first printed and ground their pressed silvers and then painted to oil with brush.
On the contrary, the structure of the 1990 copies shows that the painting was applied with a roller without directly printing the pressed silvers. In addition, it is not oil painting, but acrylic painting.
“These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from Andy Warhol’s official Brilliant Boxing list,” says Lars Nittve, the director of the Museum Moderna Museet and adds that if the “Andy Warhol Art” Authentication Commission in New York does not arrive at any conclusion, the Museum Moderna Museums will be exposing these boxes.
