Rebel soldiers surrender in Manila.
In the Philippines, the rebel soldiers who had entrenched in a hotel in Manila have surrendered and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who blames the president, corruption and electoral fraud, told a reporter he could not answer for spilling blood.
Soldiers loyal to the government had assaulted the hotel using tear gas.
Nearly two hundred soldiers had been entrenched in the building for hours.
Almost half of them, including Trillanes, were on trial Thursday for attempting a coup d'état in 2003 that ended in a failure.
He took advantage of the negotiations, to suddenly be able to deposit with about 30 supporters.
Obviously the military police officers who were supposed to watch him had passed to their ranks and followed their mutiny.
They entered the "Peninsula" hotel and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Government troops blocked the neighborhood around the Noble Hotel.
The president called an urgent session of the Security Cabinet.
Norberto Gonzales, the National Security Advisor, condemned the behavior of the soldiers.
“People are fed up,” Trillanes said.
"We call on people to move to our ranks."
General Danilo Lim, who had previously led the elite Scout Reangers troops, said that within a short time the other military troops wanted to continue the march.
The big government critics called for a big demonstration against the president on Thursday.
For months his government has been blamed for corruption.
In 2003 the financial district in Manila was a site that attracted all the attention for the mutiny that was attempted against Arroyo.
The uprising failed after about 24 hours because the army wanted to participate.
Since 1986 there have been at least seven attempted coups against the democratically elected government in the Philippines.
